{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"68f44883-f442-447b-98d8-09a49aabb725","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe project and code are fine — the bottleneck is **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild server process.\n\nHere are the fixes, ordered by impact:\n\n### 1. Enable the MSBuild Server (biggest win)\nKeeps MSBuild nodes alive between CLI invocations, just like VS does:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\n\nAdd to your shell profile (`.bashrc`/`.zshrc`) for persistence.\n\n### 2. Skip restore when packages haven't changed\n\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\n\nThe implicit `dotnet restore` on every build adds ~0.5–1s even when nothing needs restoring.\n\n### 3. Ensure MSBuild node reuse is enabled\nSome environments disable it. Make sure this is **not** set:\n\n```bash\nunset MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE   # or ensure it's 0, not 1\n```\n\n### 4. Use `dotnet watch` for edit-build-test loops\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\nThis keeps the process hot and rebuilds incrementally on file changes — closest to the VS experience.\n\n### Summary\n\n| Technique | Saves | Effort |\n|---|---|---|\n| `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` | ~1–2s (process startup) | One env var |\n| `--no-restore` | ~0.5–1s (restore check) | Per-command flag |\n| Node reuse enabled | ~0.5s (node spinup) | One env var |\n| `dotnet watch build` | All of the above | Workflow change |\n\nThe MSBuild server + `--no-restore` combo should bring CLI builds close to VS speed for this project.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7fb9ffd0-efd7-4c9b-a6d5-5e2382ed983c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer is reporting that `dotnet build` from CLI is slow (2-4 seconds) for incremental builds even when nothing has changed, while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses the MSBuild Server (a long-lived process that keeps the MSBuild node and project evaluation cached), while `dotnet build` from the CLI by default starts a new MSBuild process each time, paying the cost of:\n\n1. .NET runtime startup\n2. MSBuild node initialization\n3. Project file evaluation/parsing\n4. NuGet restore check\n5. SDK resolution\n\nThe main recommendations are:\n\n\n- Enable the MSBuild server with `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` to keep a persistent process alive and avoid repeated startup and project evaluation overhead, which is what Visual Studio does under the hood.\n- Skip the restore phase with `--no-restore` if dependencies haven't changed.\n- Use `dotnet watch` for iterative development workflows to maintain a running process across multiple builds. The MSBuild node reuse setting is important too — keeping `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE` unset or explicitly set to 0 allows nodes to persist across builds, which avoids the overhead of spinning up new processes each time.","outputTokens":1045},"id":"e5bb18bf-fdd0-4277-b441-507d8066ca07","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:51:51.470Z","parentId":"7ba2be5a-d6e2-4a44-ae6d-e0a0910cfdcf"}
